# Quick Sort

## Problem

Quick Sort is a Divide and Conquer sorting algorithm that selects a pivot element and partitions the array such that:

* elements smaller than pivot come before it
* elements greater than pivot come after it

Then the same process is applied recursively on subarrays.

---

# Algorithm / Pseudo Code

BEGIN

QUICKSORT(A, low, high)

IF low < high

    pivotIndex = PARTITION(A, low, high)

    CALL QUICKSORT(A, low, pivotIndex - 1)

    CALL QUICKSORT(A, pivotIndex + 1, high)

ENDIF

END


PARTITION(A, low, high)

SET pivot = A[high]

INITIALIZE i = low - 1

FOR j = low TO high - 1

    IF A[j] < pivot

        i = i + 1

        SWAP A[i] and A[j]

    ENDIF

ENDFOR

SWAP A[i+1] and A[high]

RETURN i + 1

END

---

# Time Complexity

| Case         | Complexity |
| ------------ | ---------- |
| Best Case    | O(n log n) |
| Average Case | O(n log n) |
| Worst Case   | O(n²)      |

---

# Space Complexity

O(log n)
---

# Important Points

* Based on Divide and Conquer.
* Uses pivot element.
* In-place sorting algorithm.
* Faster in practice than Merge Sort.
* Not stable.
